window.DYNALAB_HELP_CONTENT = {
  "settings_tamarind": {
    "title": "Tamarind Bio API key",
    "overviewHtml": "<p><strong>Tamarind Bio</strong> is an external cloud service that runs heavy protein-AI steps: roughly speaking, it can propose new binder shapes (diffusion-style), fill in sequences (MPNN-style), and score how well a binder might dock to your target (AlphaFold-Multimer-like models).</p><p>Your API key is like a password. DynaLab stores it only in <code>web/server/.env</code> on the machine running the Flask server (that file should stay out of git).</p><p>If you leave the key blank or use the mock client in the design card, the UI still works for demos—responses are fake but deterministic.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Think of the key as permission to spend Tamarind compute credits. The key is never embedded in the web page sent to your browser; the browser asks your Flask server, and the server uses the key when it forwards a design job.</p><p>If you are not ready to call a paid API, check <strong>mock client</strong> in the design section. That path exercises file handling and UI without touching Tamarind.</p><p>If you rotate or revoke a key, update Settings and save again. Old jobs on disk are unaffected; only new submissions use the updated secret.</p>"
  },
  "settings_endpoint": {
    "title": "API endpoint",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>The <strong>endpoint</strong> is the base web address Tamarind uses for its REST API—similar to how <code>https://api.example.com</code> is the front door for many services.</p><p>Almost everyone should keep the default Tamarind host unless their support team gives you a staging URL or regional mirror.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>A REST API is just structured HTTPS traffic: DynaLab packages JSON, sends it to the endpoint, and reads JSON back. If the endpoint is wrong, you will see network errors or HTML error pages instead of JSON.</p><p>Changing the endpoint does not change your science parameters; it only changes where the design request is delivered.</p><p>If you are behind a strict firewall, outbound HTTPS to that host must be allowed from the machine running Flask—not from your laptop alone unless Flask runs locally.</p>"
  },
  "upload_pdb": {
    "title": "Structure upload",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>A <strong>PDB file</strong> is a text file that lists atoms (often just heavy atoms or Cα) and their 3D coordinates. It is the usual way crystallographers and structural biologists share a starting structure.</p><figure class=\"help-modal__media\"><img src=\"media/pdb-structure.gif\" alt=\"Example protein structure rotating in 3D (cartoon representation)\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"><figcaption class=\"help-modal__caption\">Cartoons are a visualization; the PDB itself is coordinate tables, not a movie.</figcaption></figure><p>DynaLab feeds that geometry into Upside preparation so the coarse-grained model matches your protein's shape and connectivity.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>If you have never opened a PDB, open one in a text editor: you will see headers (metadata) and lines starting with ATOM or HETATM. Each line names an element and gives x,y,z in Ångströms.</p><p>A <strong>single clean chain</strong> is easiest: missing atoms, unresolved loops, and fused crystal partners all become modeling assumptions. For membrane proteins, make sure the PDB orientation matches how you will configure the membrane card.</p><p>Hydrogens are often absent in experimental PDBs—that is normal. Upside uses a coarse representation where hydrogens are implicit or grouped; the preparation step builds what the force field expects.</p><p>Very large assemblies or multi-chain viral particles can run, but they cost more time. Start with the domain you care about if you only need local unfolding behavior.</p>"
  },
  "contact_details": {
    "title": "Contact information",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>These fields are <strong>metadata only</strong>: they tag who initiated a run so shared servers, teaching labs, or core facilities can audit usage.</p><p>Nothing here changes energies, forces, or integrators—it is purely for humans reading logs or job folders later.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Treat this like signing a lab notebook page: useful when six months later you wonder who queued the 48-hour sweep.</p><p>If privacy matters, use initials or a lab role instead of a personal email. The app does not validate email format beyond basic input.</p><p>If you export or archive job directories, remember names and emails live in those JSON/metadata sidecars too.</p>"
  },
  "contact_name": {
    "title": "Name",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Stored next to the job id on the Flask host when you click run.</p><p>Helpful when multiple people share one workstation or queue.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>This is not authentication: anyone who can reach the server UI can type any name. It is a courtesy label, not access control.</p><p>If you integrate with LIMS later, this field is the obvious hook to map into an operator id.</p>"
  },
  "contact_email": {
    "title": "Email",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Optional contact string recorded with the job.</p><p>This demo does not send mail; it is only for humans browsing completed jobs.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>If you paste a shared lab inbox, everyone watching that inbox can correlate downloads—but the simulation itself does not email that address automatically.</p>"
  },
  "basic_simulation": {
    "title": "Basic simulation",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Here you choose <strong>how long</strong> to integrate, <strong>how often</strong> to save frames, and whether you simulate at one temperature or use <strong>replica exchange</strong> (several temperatures that occasionally swap coordinates).</p><p>Upside reports temperature and time in <strong>reduced units</strong> tied to its force field. Think of them as dial settings you compare across runs rather than literal lab thermometers until you do a careful calibration story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Molecular dynamics solves Newton-like equations for many particles. Short runs only explore tiny vibrations; longer runs let larger rearrangements appear, but never guarantee you will see rare events.</p><p>The <strong>frame interval</strong> controls how often you take a snapshot for movies and analysis. Saving every step is almost never necessary and creates huge files.</p><p>Replica exchange is a statistical trick: hot copies help hop barriers while cold copies stay near physiological conditions; swaps must be accepted often enough or you wasted parallel CPUs.</p><p>If a setting feels abstract, run a 30-second toy job and look at the trajectory: intuition follows from watching cartoons move.</p>"
  },
  "sim_mode": {
    "title": "Simulation mode",
    "overviewHtml": "<p><strong>Constant temperature</strong> keeps one thermostat on one copy of your protein—classic MD.</p><p><strong>Replica exchange</strong> runs several copies at different temperatures and periodically tries to swap coordinates between neighbors to improve sampling.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Constant-T mode is the default mental model: energy bumps into the bath, the bath stays at set temperature, the protein explores conformations allowed at that heat.</p><p>Replica exchange adds ladders: a very hot replica can unfold quickly, while a cool replica stays near native conditions. Swaps let the cool chain inherit beneficial moves discovered by hot chains.</p><p>If your question is only local relaxation around a crystal structure, constant temperature is simpler. If you need barrier crossings (partial unfolding without insane heat on the physical replica), replica exchange is attractive.</p>"
  },
  "duration_steps": {
    "title": "Duration (steps)",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Total number of MD integration steps before the job stops.</p><p>More steps cost more CPU but let slower motions appear; tiny runs are only smoke tests.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>An integration step is one tick of the simulation clock. The physical time per step depends on the propagator and model; Upside uses a coarse model where each step is cheap but not a literal femtosecond mapping without documentation.</p><p>If you pull or sweep forces, interesting events might occur late—too-short jobs end before the protein responds.</p><p>If you are iterating parameters, start short, then extend once plots look stable.</p>"
  },
  "frame_interval": {
    "title": "Frame interval",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Save a snapshot every <em>N</em> steps into the trajectory file.</p><p>Smaller <em>N</em> gives smoother movies and finer plots but larger files and slower analysis.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Think of frames as photographs of a race: more photos catch brief grimaces, but your album becomes heavy.</p><p>For slow observables like radius of gyration, a modest interval is fine. For rapid bond vibrations you rarely save every vibration anyway because the model is coarse.</p><p>If disk is tight, double the interval and see whether your plots change materially.</p>"
  },
  "temperature_reduced": {
    "title": "Temperature",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Thermostat target in Upside <strong>reduced</strong> units—not literal Kelvin in this UI field.</p><p>Higher values add kinetic energy and can accelerate unfolding; lower values keep the chain more frozen.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Temperature controls how vigorously random kicks jiggle the chain. In reduced units, what matters is relative comparisons between runs and the replica ladder spacing—not the absolute number by itself.</p><p>If you compare to wet lab, you need a mapping story from reduced units to physical units for your force field and model resolution—that is research-level calibration, not a single universal factor.</p><p>If the protein explodes numerically, temperature may be too high for your timestep or constraints; if nothing moves, it may be too low or your duration too short.</p>"
  },
  "replica_exchange": {
    "title": "Replica exchange",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Several simulations run in parallel at different temperatures and periodically attempt to exchange coordinates between neighbors.</p><p>Cold replicas stay near the structure you care about; hot replicas help hop barriers; exchange moves share progress between them.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Without replica exchange, you might crank heat to see rare events—but then your 'physical' chain is unrealistically hot. Replica exchange keeps a cool chain while borrowing exploration from hot chains via accepted swaps.</p><p>The <strong>replica interval</strong> sets how many MD steps occur between swap attempts. Too frequent swaps can hurt relaxation; too rare swaps under-use the ladder.</p><p>Acceptance rates matter: if temperatures are too far apart, swaps never accept; if too close, you duplicate work without benefit.</p><p>This is still not magic: if the phenomenon needs milliseconds and your model gives microseconds of effective sampling, MD may never show it.</p>"
  },
  "replica_n_replicas": {
    "title": "Number of replicas",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>How many parallel temperature rungs sit on the replica ladder.</p><p>More rungs widen the temperature span or tighten spacing—both cost CPU.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Each replica is a full copy of the system evolving at its own temperature. Doubling replicas roughly doubles wall time unless you have idle cores.</p><p>Spacing replicas evenly in temperature space is common; the UI exposes low/high and count rather than every intermediate value explicitly.</p>"
  },
  "replica_t_low": {
    "title": "T_low",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>The coldest replica's thermostat setting (reduced units).</p><p>Usually closest to the 'physiological' behavior you want to interpret.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>This is the replica whose frames you might compare most directly to experimental intuition—still coarse-grained, but not artificially scorching.</p><p>If T_low is too high, even your 'cold' chain is overheated; if too low, swaps from warm replicas may rarely propagate useful moves.</p>"
  },
  "replica_t_high": {
    "title": "T_high",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>The hottest replica on the ladder (reduced units).</p><p>Helps cross barriers that block the cold replica.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Hot replicas explore more aggressively but can look denatured—that is acceptable if swaps feed partial progress back to cold replicas.</p><p>If T_high is not hot enough, you may see no improvement over constant temperature. If absurdly hot, numerical instabilities or junk structures can appear.</p>"
  },
  "replica_interval": {
    "title": "Replica interval",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>MD steps between batches of replica swap attempts.</p><p>Shorter intervals mix more aggressively; longer intervals let each replica relax.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Swapping too often is like shaking a lava lamp every second: interfaces never settle. Swapping too rarely is like stirring once an hour: replicas stay isolated.</p><p>Watch logs or acceptance metrics if you add them later; tuning intervals is an advanced but common task.</p>"
  },
  "pulling_overview": {
    "title": "Pulling",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Adds external forces so the protein feels mechanical load similar to <strong>AFM</strong>, <strong>optical tweezers</strong>, or a <strong>centrifuge</strong> assay after calibration.</p><p>Enable only when your question involves tension, unfolding pathways, or cryptic surfaces exposed under stress.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>In the lab, pulling unfolds domains at a measured rate or force. In the model, pulling biases the energy landscape so unfolded states become accessible within simulation time.</p><p>If you do not need force, leave pulling off: extra handles add parameters and ways to misuse geometry.</p><p>Pulling is not a substitute for careful experimental geometry: attachment points, linker compliance, and surface chemistry all shift real forces.</p>"
  },
  "pulling_mode": {
    "title": "Pulling mode",
    "overviewHtml": "<p><strong>Velocity clamp (AFM-style)</strong>: a virtual spring moves at set speed; force builds as the protein resists.</p><p><strong>Constant tension</strong>: applies a target load more directly—closer to thinking in piconewtons once calibrated.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Real AFM cantilevers are springs dragged at constant speed until bonds break; the velocity-clamp mode mirrors that story line.</p><p>Constant tension is closer to 'I apply 20 pN and see how the extension drifts'—useful when your experiment holds load while fluorescence reports state.</p><p>Neither mode includes the wet-lab fluid viscosity, surface adsorption, or cantilever calibration drift; those remain interpretation layers on top.</p>"
  },
  "pulling_afm_config": {
    "title": "AFM (velocity clamp) fields",
    "overviewHtml": "<p><strong>Residue</strong> (0-based index): which Cα the spring grabs.</p><p><strong>Spring constant</strong>: stiffer spring transmits more force for the same extension (Upside reduced units).</p><p><strong>Tip position</strong> and <strong>pulling velocity</strong>: where the spring anchor lives in space and how fast it moves per step.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Indexing: most programmers count from 0; biologists often count residues from 1. If results look off by one, check this mismatch first.</p><p>The spring constant couples geometry to force: too soft and nothing happens; too stiff and integrators can become finicky.</p><p>Velocity is per integration step in Å/step in the UI fields—tiny numbers are normal. Think in orders of magnitude and watch extension traces.</p>"
  },
  "pulling_tension_config": {
    "title": "Constant tension fields",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Each row lists a residue and a tension vector <strong>(tx, ty, tz)</strong> in kT/Å units used internally.</p><p>Multiple rows can implement opposed pulls: anchor one end, tug the other.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Constant tension does not magically know your centrifuge lane calibration; pN targets in sweeps are converted using documented factors elsewhere in the pipeline.</p><p>Vectors mean direction matters: pulling along z versus x can sample different unfolding pathways.</p><p>If nothing moves, tension might be tiny relative to internal forces; if everything explodes, tension or timestep may be too aggressive.</p>"
  },
  "force_sweep": {
    "title": "Force sweep",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Runs a <strong>ladder of forces</strong> (in piconewtons after calibration), one sub-simulation per force (with optional replicas each).</p><p>This mirrors multi-lane centrifuge experiments where each lane feels a different effective load.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Single pulling answers 'what happens at one load'. Sweeping answers 'at which load does this epitope or domain cross a threshold'.</p><p>Cost scales with number of forces times replicas times duration—plan a sparse ladder first, then refine near interesting thresholds.</p><p>When sweep is enabled, the big Run button orchestrates many child jobs instead of the single configuration in card 4 alone.</p>"
  },
  "sweep_subsim": {
    "title": "Sub-simulation type",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Chooses velocity-clamp vs constant-tension physics <em>inside each</em> sweep sub-job.</p><p>Matches the same conceptual choice as the single pulling card.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>The sweep only changes the force schedule; the underlying pull mode still changes how load enters the equations.</p><p>If you mix modes between papers and simulation, document which mode matched which assay.</p>"
  },
  "sweep_forces_pn": {
    "title": "Forces (pN)",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Comma-separated list of target forces in <strong>piconewtons</strong> after your calibration story.</p><p>Example ladder: <code>14,18,22,26,30,34,38</code> spanning a biophysically interesting window.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>A piconewton is a trillionth of a newton—typical single-molecule forces live in tens to hundreds of pN.</p><p>Spacing: linear ladders are easy to interpret; adaptive refinement is a manual loop (rerun with tighter spacing near transitions).</p><p>If a value fails to parse, that sub-job may error—keep commas plain ASCII and numbers simple decimals.</p>"
  },
  "sweep_replicas": {
    "title": "Replicas per force",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Independent repeats at <em>each</em> force in the ladder.</p><p>Improves statistics for stochastic unfolding; multiplies CPU time.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Biological single-molecule traces jitter run-to-run; replicas mimic repeating the experiment under identical programmed load.</p><p>Use at least 2–3 when you will compare distributions; use 1 only for exploratory wiring.</p>"
  },
  "sweep_anchor": {
    "title": "Anchor residue",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>0-based residue treated as the fixed or reference end of the pull geometry for sweep sub-jobs.</p><p>Pairs with pull residue to define a load path through the chain.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Pick anchors that match how the protein attaches in assay: C-term His-tag immobilized implies different effective anchors than N-term fusion.</p><p>If anchor equals pull site, forces are degenerate—double-check indices.</p>"
  },
  "sweep_pull_residue": {
    "title": "Pull residue",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>0-based residue where the pulling potential applies.</p><p>Use <strong>-1</strong> to mean the last residue—common for C-terminal handles.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>The pull site should coincide with the chemistry that actually feels the bead or surface in your experimental construct.</p><p>Off-by-one errors between sequence numbering and PDB numbering are a classic pitfall; verify against a structure viewer.</p>"
  },
  "membrane": {
    "title": "Membrane",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Adds implicit membrane boundaries so membrane proteins feel confinement similar to a bilayer slab.</p><p>Disable for soluble-only systems; tune inner/outer limits when enabled.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>This is not an explicit lipid bilayer with every tail: it is a simplified potential that captures the large-scale effect of being embedded.</p><p>Orientation matters: your PDB must sit in the coordinate frame expected by the slab definition.</p><p>If the protein drifts out of the slab, recentering options or boundary choices may be wrong.</p>"
  },
  "membrane_coord_system": {
    "title": "Membrane coordinate system",
    "overviewHtml": "<p><strong>Cartesian</strong>: slab normal along z; inner/outer are z limits.</p><p><strong>Spherical</strong>: alternate convention for specialized Upside setups—only if your preparation matches.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>If you are unsure, Cartesian is the common teaching picture: membrane horizontal in the xy plane, thickness along z.</p><p>Mismatch here is a silent science bug: the protein can be 'in membrane' numerically while visually outside in a viewer if frames are rotated.</p>"
  },
  "membrane_inner_bound": {
    "title": "Inner membrane boundary",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>One edge of the membrane slab in Ångströms.</p><p>Together with the outer boundary defines where the implicit membrane acts.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Inner vs outer naming follows the Upside convention for the slab; visually verify in a structure viewer which leaflet is which for your PDB.</p><p>If boundaries hug the protein too tightly, steric clashes or artificial squeezing can appear.</p>"
  },
  "membrane_outer_bound": {
    "title": "Outer membrane boundary",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>The opposite slab face from the inner boundary (Å).</p><p>Adjust until the protein sits in the intended region.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Think of the two boundaries like the walls of a narrow elevator shaft: the chain should ride comfortably between them.</p><p>If water or headgroup chemistry matters for your question, remember those details are not atomically resolved here.</p>"
  },
  "membrane_recenter_opts": {
    "title": "Membrane recentering",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Controls whether the simulation periodically recenters the system relative to the membrane.</p><p>Turn off only if you deliberately want drift or have an exotic setup.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Periodic boxes can make proteins appear to slide; recentering keeps the biology interpretable in Cartesian viewers.</p><p>Wrong recentering can 'yank' a protein out of the slab—if that happens, revisit boundaries and these toggles.</p>"
  },
  "restraints": {
    "title": "Restraints",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Extra springs or walls that pin atoms, keep distances, or mimic attachment points.</p><p>Text formats mirror Upside preparation tables—typos become silent or loud failures at prep time.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Restraints are mathematical rubber bands: cheap computationally but easy to over-constrain so the physics is no longer representative.</p><p>Use the smallest restraint that enforces your experimental symmetry (e.g., pinned termini for an AFM handle).</p><p>Each subtype (wall vs spring vs nail) encodes different geometry—read the inline card examples slowly.</p>"
  },
  "restraint_fixed_wall": {
    "title": "Fixed wall restraint",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Each line: <code>residue radius spring_const wall_type x0 y0 z0</code>.</p><p>Keeps a residue outside a spherical wall centered at a fixed point.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Imagine an invisible ping-pong ball the residue cannot enter: the wall_type and radius set the geometry; the spring constant sets how sharply you bounce off.</p><p>Use when you want a steric exclusion zone (e.g., a surface) without modeling every surface atom.</p>"
  },
  "restraint_pair_wall": {
    "title": "Pair wall restraint",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Each line: <code>residue1 residue2 radius spring_const</code>.</p><p>Enforces a minimum distance between two residues.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Pair walls mimic 'these two parts cannot interpenetrate beyond this contact distance'—looser than a bond, tighter than free flight.</p><p>Good for approximate excluded volume between domains when you do not want a full spring connecting them.</p>"
  },
  "restraint_fixed_spring": {
    "title": "Fixed spring restraint",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Each line: <code>residue spring_const x0 y0 z0</code>.</p><p>Harmonic spring tying a residue toward a fixed coordinate.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>This is the AFM-like idea in miniature: a point in space attracts a residue with a quadratic penalty.</p><p>High spring constants behave like rigid tethers; low constants allow breathing.</p>"
  },
  "restraint_pair_spring": {
    "title": "Pair spring restraint",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Each line: <code>residue1 residue2 radius spring_const</code>.</p><p>Spring-like coupling between two residues as consumed by Upside prep.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Use when two sites should feel an attractive or repulsive bias relative to one another beyond ordinary nonbonded interactions.</p><p>Check units and signs in the Upside documentation—this UI only forwards your table faithfully.</p>"
  },
  "restraint_nail": {
    "title": "Nail restraint",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Each line: <code>residue spring_const</code>.</p><p>Very strong pinning of a residue—use sparingly.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Think of a nail through a board: you freeze a spot so the rest of the chain can flap.</p><p>Overuse nails artificial crystal artifacts into the trajectory; prefer the weakest nail that still enforces your boundary condition.</p>"
  },
  "run_simulation": {
    "title": "Run",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Packages your PDB and configuration, launches Upside (or the sweep orchestrator) on the Flask host, and streams logs into <code>web/server/jobs/&lt;id&gt;/</code>.</p><p>Requires name, email, and a selected PDB; additional cards add optional physics.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Nothing here runs in your browser: the browser is a remote control for the server process.</p><p>If the button stays disabled, required fields are missing or the UI thinks the form is incomplete.</p><p>If sweep is enabled, the same button fans out many child jobs—watch disk and CPU accordingly.</p>"
  },
  "progress_tracking": {
    "title": "Progress",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Parses the simulation log for step counts vs target and coarse status text.</p><p>Long jobs can sit apparently still while the integrator grinds—refresh patience first.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Progress bars are best-effort: they depend on log formatting from the engine version you run.</p><p>If a job fails early, the bar may jump to failure text instead of 100%—read the log card when available.</p>"
  },
  "results_download": {
    "title": "Results",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Finished jobs expose the trajectory file (Upside/HDF5 style <code>.up</code>) for download.</p><p>That file feeds downstream analysis checkboxes.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Trajectories are the raw experimental record of the simulation: every analysis is a derived view.</p><p>If downloads fail, check browser pop-up blockers and reverse-proxy size limits for large files.</p>"
  },
  "post_analysis_overview": {
    "title": "Post-processing analysis",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Each checkbox triggers a Python analysis on the server that rereads the trajectory and emits plots plus JSON summaries.</p><p>Some analyses are cheap scalars; others (contacts, clustering) are heavier—toggle only what you need.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Post-processing does not change the saved trajectory; it only creates sibling artifacts under the job directory.</p><p>Order of operations: finish MD, download if you want a local copy, then run analyses against the server-side file.</p><p>No checkbox replaces experimental validation: these are computational observables tied to a specific force field and resolution.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_rg": {
    "title": "Radius of gyration (Rg)",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Rg measures how spread out the mass is around its center: compact proteins have small Rg; stretched or unfolded chains have large Rg.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Rg is a single number per frame computed from atomic or Cα positions and masses (depending on implementation). It is like asking 'how big is the cloud of atoms?'.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Under force, Rg often rises when domains detach or the chain elongates along the pull axis.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Rg is blind to shape details: two different shapes can share the same Rg. Pair it with end-to-end distance, contact maps, or visuals.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_rmsd": {
    "title": "RMSD",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>RMSD (root-mean-square deviation) compares the current structure to a reference frame—usually the first saved frame—and reports how far atoms moved on average.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>RMSD is computed after superimposing structures to remove overall translation/rotation, so it focuses on internal deformation rather than drifting through space.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>When pulling unfolds a domain, RMSD often climbs because the internal arrangement no longer matches the starting crystal-like pose.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Large flexible loops can dominate RMSD even when the core is fine; interpret alongside per-residue RMSF.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_rmsf": {
    "title": "RMSF",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>RMSF (root-mean-square fluctuation) is per residue: it tells you which parts of the chain jiggle a lot vs stay rigid over the trajectory.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>After aligning frames, each atom's variance around its average position is summarized; peaks highlight loops and hinges.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Under tension, flexible epitope-containing loops may spike in RMSF right before or during exposure events.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>RMSF is not dynamics timescales: a residue can fluctuate quickly or slowly yet show similar variance if the amplitude is large.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_e2e": {
    "title": "End-to-end distance",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Distance between the first and last Cα atoms—simple scalar stretch measure for single-chain constructs.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>If your construct is one continuous chain, end-to-end tracks how much the termini separate under load.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>In pulling, rising end-to-end often tracks global unraveling along the pull vector when handles are termini.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>If your functional site is mid-chain, pair this with local distance monitors or contact maps; end-to-end can miss mid-domain opening.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_hbonds": {
    "title": "Hydrogen bonds",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Counts backbone hydrogen bonds per frame using a geometric criterion (Baker–Hubbard style).</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Secondary structure elements like helices and sheets are stabilized by patterns of hydrogen bonds; losing them often tracks unfolding.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Under force, hydrogen-bond counts may drop as helices peel or sheets fray.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>This is still a geometric proxy: it does not equal free energy of folding and can mis-count in coarse models.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_salt": {
    "title": "Salt bridges",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Approximates salt-bridge-like contacts using Cβ distances—fast and coarse-grained friendly, not a full electrostatic energy.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Salt bridges are attractive interactions between oppositely charged side chains; they stabilize many protein interfaces.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Force can disrupt salt bridges as charged groups separate, sometimes correlating with functional exposure.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Because the metric is simplified, do not over-interpret single bond counts—look for sustained trends.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_shape": {
    "title": "Shape descriptors",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Scalars derived from the gyration tensor: asphericity, acylindricity, and anisotropy describe whether the mass distribution is spherical, cigar-like, or pancake-like.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>These numbers summarize 3D shape without rendering a picture—useful for automated sweeps.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Under tension proteins often elongate: anisotropy and asphericity move in characteristic directions.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>They are global summaries: combine with contact maps when shape changes are subtle or localized.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_crosscorr": {
    "title": "Cross-correlation",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Measures correlated motion between residues: who moves together or opposite over time.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Allostery is 'motion at a distance': a perturbation at site A changes dynamics at site B. Cross-correlation helps visualize that coupling network.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Under load, mechanical propagation can show up as streaks of positive correlation along the pull pathway.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Correlation is not causation: statistical coupling can arise from many degenerate pathways.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_ss": {
    "title": "Secondary structure",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Assigns helix/sheet/coil labels over time using DSSP when installed, otherwise a simplified hydrogen-bond fallback.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Secondary structure is the local repeating backbone pattern: α-helices look like coils, β-sheets look like ladders in cartoons.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Unfolding under force often shows sheets or helices converting to coil in regions that were structured at rest.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>DSSP needs backbone geometry compatible with its assumptions; missing atoms or extreme distortions reduce reliability.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_pca": {
    "title": "PCA",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Principal component analysis finds the dominant collective motions in the set of Cα frames—usually the first few modes capture most variance.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Imagine approximating a wiggling protein path as a sum of a few simple 'shapes' of motion; PCA discovers those shapes from data.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Useful to see global opening/closing or hinge motions under force without hand-picking a reaction coordinate.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Too many components overfit noise; too few miss nuance. Start with 2–3 for plotting, then justify more if needed.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_force_ext": {
    "title": "Force vs extension",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Builds approximate force–extension curves from pulling geometry recorded in the trajectory plus job metadata.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>An AFM trace is force vs tip extension; this analysis tries to put simulation on comparable axes after calibration assumptions.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Compare qualitative shapes (sawtooth, ripples, plateaus) to experiment, not absolute numbers without calibration.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Approximate: coarse models omit many physical effects present in real tips and buffers.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_contacts": {
    "title": "Contact map",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Shows how often pairs of residues are within a cutoff distance across the trajectory—heatmap style.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Contacts reveal which parts of the protein touch; stable cores stay dark; opening shows as fading or shifting patches.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Under force, long-range contacts between termini may break while new local contacts appear transiently.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Heavy to compute: expect longer runtime and larger memory than scalar plots.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_burial": {
    "title": "Burial scan",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Tracks a solvent exposure proxy per residue over time to see when side chains become more solvent-accessible.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Cryptic epitopes are sometimes hidden in grooves until tension opens the groove; burial scans hunt that signature.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Pair with structural snapshots at the same frames to avoid over-reading a single scalar curve.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Exposure metrics depend on probe radius and coarse representation; compare runs only with identical settings.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_dihedral": {
    "title": "Dihedral unfolding",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Summarizes how backbone Ramachandran basins shift from start to end of the trajectory.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Each residue's backbone has two main dihedral angles (φ, ψ); preferred combinations define helices vs sheets.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Useful when secondary structure labels say 'coil' but you want to see if angles hop between basins gradually.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Interpretation benefits from molecular graphics literacy; if new, pair with secondary structure plots first.</p>"
  },
  "analysis_cluster": {
    "title": "Intermediate clustering",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Clusters trajectory frames in a contact-based feature space and writes representative PDBs into <code>intermediates/</code> for downstream design.</p><p>Use it together with other plots: one metric rarely tells the whole story.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<h4>If you are completely new to MD</h4><p>A molecular dynamics (MD) simulation is a computer experiment where the protein is treated as a collection of atoms (or simplified sites) that move under approximate physics. You get a movie of structures called a trajectory.</p><p>Clustering answers 'how many distinct shapes did we visit?' rather than 'what is the average structure?'.</p><h4>Why this matters under force</h4><p>Under heterogeneous unfolding, you may get separate clusters for native-like, partially unfolded, and fully stretched states.</p><h4>How to read the plot cautiously</h4><p>Choosing cluster medoids for AI design is a scientific judgment: outliers may be artifacts if clustering noise dominates.</p>"
  },
  "backmapping": {
    "title": "All-atom back-mapping",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Upside is coarse-grained: it does not keep every atom explicit. <strong>PULCHRA</strong> rebuilds an all-atom PDB from Cα geometry.</p><p>Optional minimization can relax clashes if OpenMM is installed.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Many downstream tools (diffusion, docking, MPNN) expect full atom types and bond chemistry; back-mapping is the bridge step.</p><p>Back-mapping is reconstructive guesswork: validate stereochemistry in a viewer before trusting hydrogens or unusual residues.</p><p>If minimization is off, clashes may remain; if on, watch that minimization does not erase the unfolded state you cared about.</p>"
  },
  "ai_design": {
    "title": "AI nanobody design",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Sends a chosen snapshot through an external stack that proposes binder backbones, fills sequences, and scores predicted complexes (Tamarind).</p><p>Mock mode runs a deterministic stub for demos without API keys or billing.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Think of three stages: (1) propose shapes that might dock, (2) choose sequences that fold, (3) score predicted binding quality.</p><p>Outputs are hypotheses, not drugs: expression, immunogenicity, and wet binding still dominate real programs.</p><p>Costs and latency scale with how many backbones and sequences you request—start small while learning the UI.</p>"
  },
  "design_intermediate": {
    "title": "Intermediate state",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Pick which clustered, back-mapped PDB best represents the partially unfolded 'target face' you want binders against.</p><p>Usually comes from the clustering analysis outputs.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>The same raw trajectory can yield different medoids; your scientific story should justify which state is the design target.</p><p>If the snapshot is barely unfolded, binders may not gain cryptic-site specificity you hoped for.</p>"
  },
  "design_hotspots": {
    "title": "Hotspot residues",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Comma-separated residue indices where you want the binder to make contact—often from epitope prediction or exposure plots.</p><p>Guides the external model toward biologically relevant interfaces.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Hotspots are soft hints: algorithms may still deviate if other contacts lower energy dramatically.</p><p>Use 0-based indices consistent with the uploaded PDB used throughout the job.</p>"
  },
  "design_n_backbones": {
    "title": "Number of backbones",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>How many distinct backbone scaffolds the diffusion-style sampler requests before sequence design.</p><p>More diversity increases exploration and cost.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>If you request many backbones early, you may drown in similar solutions—iterate with small counts first.</p><p>Diversity interacts with binder length and hotspot patterns; expect to tune jointly.</p>"
  },
  "design_binder_length": {
    "title": "Binder length",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Target length in amino acids for the designed binder.</p><p>Longer chains can bury more interface but are harder to express and fold.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Nanobodies are single-domain antibodies; their natural lengths inform sensible starting ranges.</p><p>If length is mismatched to epitope size, you may get frustrated loops or incomplete coverage.</p>"
  },
  "design_n_seqs_mpnn": {
    "title": "MPNN sequences per backbone",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>How many sequence variants ProteinMPNN proposes per backbone scaffold.</p><p>More sequences explore sequence space but increase compute and API time.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Sequence design assumes the backbone is reasonable; fix backbone issues before cranking sequences.</p><p>Use diversity where experimental throughput can screen many candidates; otherwise keep small.</p>"
  },
  "design_use_mock": {
    "title": "Mock client",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>When enabled, the server uses a deterministic offline stub instead of Tamarind.</p><p>No API key, no charges—ideal for CI, teaching, or UI testing.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Mock outputs look structurally plausible at a glance but are not biophysical predictions.</p><p>Switch mocks off only when you are ready to spend credits and have keys configured.</p>"
  },
  "centrifuge_experiment": {
    "title": "Centrifuge experiment design",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Generates a bench-oriented markdown sheet mapping rotor zones, force ranges, attachment chemistry, and predicted thresholds.</p><p>Bridges simulation language to what a human does at the bench.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>The sheet is a communication artifact for teams: it does not replace SOPs or safety review for real rotors.</p><p>Fill forces and zones honestly to match the hardware you own; otherwise predictions misalign with reality.</p>"
  },
  "exp_zones": {
    "title": "Radial zones",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>How many discrete radial lanes or bins you will use in the tube/rotor experiment.</p><p>Matches stratifying g-force exposure across positions.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Each zone can map to a different effective load on the protein construct if calibration is done carefully.</p><p>If you mismatch zone count vs simulation ladder, overlays become harder to read.</p>"
  },
  "exp_force_range_low": {
    "title": "Force range (low)",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Lower end of the experimental pN window for the protocol sheet.</p><p>Should pair with the high end to span the regime you test.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Choose based on instrument sensitivity and the forces where your readout changes in pilot data.</p><p>If low is near zero, remember surface-specific detachment forces can dominate near the bottom of the range.</p>"
  },
  "exp_force_range_high": {
    "title": "Force range (high)",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Upper end of the experimental pN window for the protocol sheet.</p><p>Must exceed the low end.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Rotor geometry and column height determine achievable ranges; do not copy literature numbers blindly.</p><p>If high forces risk denaturation unrelated to your epitope, note that in the attachment chemistry section.</p>"
  },
  "exp_thresholds_list": {
    "title": "Predicted thresholds",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Comma-separated pN values from simulation that you want printed on the bench sheet as reference lines.</p><p>Example: predicted exposure onset forces from burial scans.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Thresholds are hypotheses until validated against fluorescence or binding assays.</p><p>Use separate thresholds for distinct conformational events if the biology has multiple steps.</p>"
  },
  "exp_attachment_chemistry": {
    "title": "Attachment chemistry",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Free text describing how the protein attaches to the surface (His-tag/Ni-NTA, biotin/streptavidin, covalent linker, etc.).</p><p>Changes how you interpret force at the protein–surface junction.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>The same nominal rotor g-force can produce different protein tension depending on linker compliance and orientation.</p><p>Good notes here prevent collaborators from mixing incompatible constructs when comparing lanes.</p>"
  },
  "wetlab_csv": {
    "title": "Wet-lab CSV",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Upload a CSV of measured fluorescence (or similar) vs force with columns like <code>force_pN</code>, <code>fluorescence</code>, <code>replicate</code>, <code>condition</code>.</p><p>Lets the server overlay experimental batches against computational predictions.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Tidy data beats pretty spreadsheets: one row per observation, consistent units, ASCII commas.</p><p>Document what fluorescence means (FRET pair, dye quenching, etc.) in your lab notebook; the CSV cannot carry full prose safely.</p>"
  },
  "pred_threshold_pn": {
    "title": "Predicted threshold (pN)",
    "overviewHtml": "<p>Single scalar threshold from simulation (e.g., onset of exposure) used when comparing to uploaded wet-lab curves.</p><p>Drawn as a vertical reference on comparison plots.</p>",
    "detailHtml": "<p>Pick the threshold from the same analysis pipeline you trust scientifically, not an arbitrary round number.</p><p>If multiple events exist, run separate comparisons or extend the tool later—this field is one scalar by design.</p>"
  }
};
